Yes -- absolutely -- we cannot give up. Will we always have another priority since the new and now take our attention away? Yes. We have to remember slow and steady wins the race, and this has to be a long-term plan to change things for the better. Glad renewable resources are getting cheaper than coal; that shift in mentality will be slow, but only benefits us in the long run. I don't have kids, so the family name ends with me, but for my nieces and nephew, and all the future generations, we need to do better for them.

This is the issue though -- renewable power (particularly wind) is insanely cheap due to almost-zero marginal cost which means wholesale electricity in renewables is NEGATIVE (ie producers are PAYING the grid to take their electricity). There is an issue now because electricity operators follow a 'merit order' where renewables will always be chosen for dispatch first, which sets the base 'one for all' energy price. Why bother then? You can't expect these companies to be running as a charity. How are we supposed to get more renewables on the grid then? Sadly the only answer is absolutely massive government subsidies which will run in perpetuity.
